properties.name: Building permit process:independent neighbor person must agree that paperwork matches real life

comments.comment: Not eligible - not a capital project. This idea was shared with Inspectional Services.

properties.description:
A store shut down and some red "C" permit papers were placed in the windows. Grid-like framing of 2"X4" studs were attached to the exterior of the old existing facade, and then added onto the 2"X4" studs was a new wood facade. This resulted in the front of the store pushing out 5 inches. In other words, the sidewalk became 5 inches narrower and it is now the narrowest section of sidewalk on the block which has elderly housing with wheelchairs. The windows now sit deep in the swollen thick facade. The building inspector for this area of Cambridge won employee of the year. Either the owner had special permission to build out into the sidewalk unlike any other building on the block (hard to believe), or the builder did this expansion with the city building inspector having no clue. 
The way to fix the building permit process is to include an independent neighbor person who must sign and agree that construction paperwork approved by the city matches what really happens in real life.

The Cambridge housing market has become unreasonably unaffordable with successful buyers paying in cash and at well-over the asking price. This is pushing out would-be buyers who could afford to pay decent-sized mortgages and income taxes to help the city but can't compete with those buyers or pay a 20% downpayment of $100,000 or more. Low-income housing is also a problem.

The city should partner and provide incentives to a private developer who sets aside a percentage of units for not only low-income housing units but middle-income units as well. In return, in order to qualify for such units, potential buyers shall sign a contract committing to give back to the city of Cambridge through a variety of means including civic engagement and volunteerism.

What do our fire trucks, professional ambulances, police project tow trucks, and giant utility trucks in Cambridge all have in common?  They pump out choking blue-black exhaust that the regular FedEx and UPS delivery trucks are not allowed to do.  Most air pollution in Cambridge is produced by the city. Make all city trucks, and city contracted trucks, obey the same emission rules as the regular public.
Why do ambulances drive & race madly, but once at the address, the drivers stay seated checking cell phones & putting on rubber gloves 1-finger at a time and SLOWLY open their doors & step out. There is no sense of urgency. Because they are not really used as 1st responders, they should drive to the address obeying the speed limit & with no sirens.
Last, all of these trucks when not on a call should obey the 5 minute engine idle law. People who live near take-out restaurants are being choked.

properties.description: A walking tour of this neighborhood is one of pointing out where changes have made things needlessly worse. This is because the neighborhood residents always the ones to actually use the public sidewalks or park have no meaningful say in the changes. New sidewalk setbacks do look mighty nice while looking out from a city car, but for the local neighborhood people commuting by foot every day, they have lost the awnings overhead which had provided shelter from rain.  They have lost close abutting wallfronts which had provided to all on the sidewalks shade from the blazing summer sun.  Inside the parks, utility and functionality is needlessly lost, but, hey, new designs from the high paid office expert all look mighty nice looking from afar while driving by in a city truck or car. Thanks for the comments. I agree on marking trees if possible which could note that they were paid for via the Participatory Budgeting process. Also having commitments to maintain them is key - perhaps a 2 or 3 year watering commitment from the City and replacement guaranty from the contractor for 2 or 3 years. Most importantly, trees should be planted not only in empty tree wells (which I think the City has inventoried already) but in all potential locations - please take note of areas in your neighborhood where there is no canopy and post them here. For inspiration, several other cities have made big commitments to increasing their tree canopies including:  
1) Boston has committed to “increase [its] tree canopy to 35% by 2030.”      
2) New York City has committed to “planting street trees in all possible locations.” The project “will work steadily over the next decade to plant 220,000 new street trees.”  See: www.milliontreesnyc.org/html/million_trees/commitment.shtml

Note that part of the problem is that trees die and are not replaced.  One of the reasons they die is lack of maintenance - trees are not watered, tree gratings are missing - resulting in soil compaction, the openings in tree gratings are not enlarged when the trees grow - resulting to damage to the trunk and bark.  From the way this ideas list is described, funding to address maintenance wouldn't be appropriate here, but it's important.  Could some of the money be used to create a tree care endowment?
Excellent idea!
Great idea.

I love this idea. I'm very concerned by the loss of mature canopy in recent years, and this proposal could be a wonderful way to energize the community and green our city. Maybe funding could also go toward protecting the mature trees we have. I've noticed that we lose trees to NSTAR's aggressive overtrimming, which results in tree death and tree removal. If the city had the money and a mandate, there are solutions to some tree issues that are less extreme and could preserve some of our canopy. At any rate, I'm thrilled to see a thoughtful, hopeful proposal reminding us of how important trees are to our health and our community. I'm all for it. Thank you!

The first step everyone could take is to make a list of empty tree wells because most, but not all, of them are eligible for a new tree.  Cambridgeport did that several years ago.  Neighborhood associations across the city could initiate the inventory in their neighborhood.  These lists could be submitted to the Arborist and a meeting could be arranged to discuss the community's requests.  Keep in mind that the ADA rules require sidewalk width of at least 4 ft. not including tree wells, planter areas or the space needed for the door of a building to open onto the sidewalk area.   Therefore, where some trees have been removed because they were sick or dead a replacement tree can be planted only if there is enough sidewalk clearance per ADA regulations.  In some cases, in many cases, there is not enough sidewalk clearance to meet the ADA regulations and a replacement tree cannot be planted.  That is why the city initiated the back of sidewalk tree planting program.  In addition to empty tree wells, there are tree wells that were cemented over.  These former tree wells are supposed to be classified as tree wells still and a request can be made to plant a replacement tree there as well.   As far as maintaining the young trees, that must be accomplished with paid tree care workers.  Although the arborist puts the tree-gators around new trees, it is rare that one is filled with water.   A notice is placed on the doorknob of the residence nearest the new tree with instructions on how to care for the new tree.  It seems such notices are for naught.   Good idea, but people don't seem to care and just toss the notice. The city hired a few people to go around on a bicycle fitted with a trailer of some type for supplies so that they could water trees.  There are not enough of these tree care staffers to meet the need.  Money could very easily be allocated from Free Cash to the budget of the Parks & Forest Dept. for the purpose of providing such care.  Although the supplier must guarantee new trees for a year, it is a pity to lose a year's worth of growth for such new trees.  And, what's to say, the next tree won't die for lack of water because no one in the community cares for the tree?

Totally support this idea, especially if it could include some way to engage immediate neighbors in the care of planted trees (a city-sponsored tree care mobile app for instance, where each tree was bar-coded or QR-coded so that neighbors could send in requests for watering, pruning etc on the spot from our mobile phones

properties.description:
Combining 2 proposals & adding detail, I propose planting 1,000 trees throughout the city & purchase of equip to water for 2 summers when they’re most fragile. 

The city could identify streets with the least canopy to focus where benefits are greatest. As NYC proposed, we can plant in every possible location, not only replace dead trees. City, CHA & back-of-sidewalk locations are eligible.

We’re losing our large legacy trees & new saplings cannot keep up. Yet trees benefit us by:
- providing shade, keeping people, buildings & homes cooler
- reducing storm-water & "heat island effect," lowering AC use & GHG emissions, saving $ in sync with Net Zero efforts
- sequestering GHGs, removing pollutants & adding oxygen
- reducing asthma, lowering stress & other health benefits
- making our urban landscape more pleasant
- providing habitat & connecting us to ecosystems

Trees could be marked as funded via PB so the info & benefits of tree planting are distributed around the City.

properties.description:
Cycling is on the rise in Cambridge, but not all residents find it practical to bring their bikes inside at the end of the day.  Covered outdoor parking sprinkled through the city's neighborhoods would combine the convenience of leaving your bike outside with protection from the elements and rust.  While sidewalk space is at a premium, there are many suitable sites (especially near intersections) where covered parking for 4-8 bikes could be installed without obstructing pedestrian and wheelchair access.   The most useful place to have the racks would be in the middle of dense residential neighborhoods, rather than in commercial squares.

The participatory budget would fund a pilot program for installing several covered bike racks in neighborhoods and then collecting feedback from cyclists who use them.  Based on the use patterns for the covered parking and cyclist satisfaction level, the City could then evaluate installing them on a more widespread basis in every neighborhood.

comments.comment: Budget Delegates did not rank this as a high priority project.

This 3-way intersection is long overdue for safety improvements. Turning from Sparks onto Brattle is very difficult and confusing especially at rush hour when school children are crossing. The bike lane on Sparks makes it even more important to signal rights of way.

properties.description: This intersection has quickly-moving traffic on a curved section of Brattle with traffic from Sparks and Craigie also entering. Something needs to be done to smooth vehicular traffic during rush hours, but for now this proposal focuses on pedestrian safety while crossing Brattle and also the mouth of lower Sparks Street (drivers often fly off of Brattle onto Sparks without seeing pedestrians because of the angle of the road's curve). I would like the city to study the intersection and install some pedestrian signals that clearly stop traffic in all directions if deemed appropriate.

properties.name: Use part of city-owned DPW land to provide playground/park in this dense neighborhood

comments.comment: Not feasible - space required for DPW operations.
Clearly the Norfolk St. Parking lot needs maintenance but there must be street repair funds for this.  Play and greenspace would be an important improvement.

I just want to add that the need is greater in this area, with its highly dense population. Open space per 1,000 citizens is a map available on the Cambridge GIS web page. If you take a look, you can see that this area and its many children who are residents have little to no open space recreation options, as compared with neighborhood in West and North Cambridge particularly.

The unequal distribution of green, open space for children to experience in the city could be addressed within this proposal, with the addition of a natural [discovery], free-play area. How about a play area that is not just a playground, with enormous logs to clamber on, use as "balance beams," etc.. This could be similar to the one projected for the top of Kingsley Park at Fresh Pond Res., but fitting the space—with natural plantings to attract birds (with perhaps some bird and bat houses high up in the trees; bats eat mosquitoes, after all!). Kids would benefit from enough space to run, play hide and seek, and play inventive games (rather than the more limited activity you can get from swings and slides alone).

I echo all of the above remarks concerning the DPW yard. Open space, a park (there are more kids in the neighborhood than there were just a few years ago), and a public walk way connecting Norfolk St. would make the city's impingement here a lot easier to swallow.

A public park with a walkway connecting two dead ends of Norfolk would be a wonderful addition, here! Especially with the recent development in Inman Square, it would really help improve the neighborhood...

The DPW yard had once been a park many years ago. According to a neighbor born in a house at the corner of Cambridge and Columbia St. in the 1920's the DPW yard had a public "bath" house with a public swimming pool. In the early 1970's, the city turned it into a truck yard and the community lost open space. It's time to get some public open space back.

Over the past few summers, parents from the Tobin School have hosted a series of play-dates for in-coming/new students and their families. In evaluating how to improve these gatherings, many of us agreed that HEAT has been an issue. This proposal responds by creating more SHADE! It will meet a real need, in a very cost-effective way.

So much thoughtful expert research proves that creative play engages our imagination and is a critical component of child development.  Innovative playgrounds that are designed to encourage children to imagine, explore and discover are vital to the learning process.  Urban playgrounds that use nature as play elements expose children to fundamental concepts that they may not experience in their formative years. This neighborhood playground adjacent to CPS's Tobin is a TRULY UNIQUE opportunity to be a model for learning through play in a natural environment. Even simple interventions like trees and shrubs could make a significant impact, but I fully support the idea of re-thinking how this playground can be transformed from a conventional play space into an innovative natural play environment that expresses this city's values and commitment to be an innovation hub for learning and living.

properties.name: Proper Pruning of Trees Near Electric Wires

comments.comment: Budget Delegates did not rank this as a high priority project.
Good idea Cheyenne, I support this.

properties.description: On streets with above ground wires neither the city or private landscape companies will prune back trees that are dangerously interacting with electrical wires. It is left to NSTAR to "prune" the trees back. However, NSTAR is more invested in their wires than the trees.They cut off all branches on either side of the wires. A gaping hole of cut off limbs in the middle remains and the shape of the tree becomes like a Y. This is structurally not sound for the tree as it matures. I'd like to see the establishment of a policy on how to properly prune trees near wires that protects the wires AND the trees. NSTAR should be expected to pay a fine ( that goes toward tree care ) if they violate the policy.

The play structures should be updated to engage a wider range of children. There is space to expand the community garden area to address the long waiting list of potential gardeners and even to construct a children’s garden.  The exit to busy Walden Street should be reconfigured to make it safer for small children.

comments.comment: This project won funding! 100 new trees will be planted in FY16 (in addition to the trees Public Works was already planning to plant).

properties.description: The tree canopy in the city is disappearing due to lack of 1:1 or greater than replacement of removed trees.  Also there is an increased impervious surface as the city increases in density, and greater percentage of the lots are covered in buildings and asphalt.  The advantage of using these funds for trees is that they can be spent in every part of the city!

properties.name: Fixing Inman Square crosswalk lights & park seating

comments.comment: Budget Delegates did not rank this as a high priority project. Inman Square traffic study to improve the area will begin in spring 2015.

Why should Inman Square be unsafe for pedestrians?  Thanks to this web site, the solution has been found.  In Union Square all traffic stops and people walk.  With every light cycle, all traffic stops and people walk.  It is safe and orderly.  All traffic stops, and people walk!

Fix Inman Square.

Fix Inman Square.

Fix Inman Square.

very practical-why not learn from what has already been done successfully in Union Square.
Shade trees would be a great improvement too.
I second this. Shade could also be had with more trees
good practical ideas.

properties.description:
Crossing the street in Inman Square is unsafe. Drivers do not believe pedestrians are seeking a walk signal because of the poor design and timing. I have seen many fights, even with elderly pedestians. Unsafe and shameful. But, easy and cost-free to fix. Simply copy timing system of Union Square where ALL TRAFFIC STOPS and all pedestrians see a walk signal during each light cycle.  Simple.

The summer shaded seating at the Valucci Memorial Tribute Park in Inman Square has been blocked for 3 or 4 years now by the bike rental station. In the hot summer, only seating under the sun is open.  Poor design by people who do not live near this park.  Easy and cost-free to fix.  Either pushout the bike rental station 2 feet away from the shaded seating (give a 2 foot space between the seating and bike station), or move the bike rental station to the hot sun-drenched side of the park.

properties.name: Exercise equipment

comments.comment: This project made it to the ballot (location was moved to Danehy Park), but did not receive enough votes to win funding.

@Sarah D: The particular stretch I selected is mown grass and light landscaping next to the parking lot.  I don't think that it will be disruptive to the rest of the property's native planting and naturalistic feel.

@Harvey:  Sounds good!  I'll check it out.

Hi Seth,

I think we have the same idea! Find ours on the map in Danehy Park next to the running track. We lived in Atlanta before moving to Cambridge, and had access to Piedmont Park in Midtown with incredible outdoor fitness opportunities. It would be great if Cambridge would adopt this idea too. Check out our presentation and get in touch if you want to collaborate: http://youtu.be/6JPLIquqdPE
this is not a very natural environment  - so I think it would be great to have some equipment here - great idea!
There is so little open space left natural. I prefer LESS man-made objects - Let's keep it a beautiful natural area.
Agree.

properties.description:
There's only one set of exercise equipment in the Cambridge parks.  Chicago has them all along Lake Michigan and I think they are a great public benefit.
This stretch of the Fresh Pond path would be perfect to setup a few well-spaced stations.  You can also include some signage for people explaining the various exercises.
-Pull-up bar
-Inverted row bars
-Parallel bars
-Dip station
-Inclined leg-raises
-Sit-ups
-Slanted wooden fence for jumping over
-Something for plyometrics
-Back extension

You might be able to recruit someone looking for an eagle scout project to assist.

For an example, using Street View in Google Maps, start at the Diversey Miniature Golf Course in Chicago and head north on the gravel running path.

properties.name: Walking Trail Guide. A paper and online map of walks of various lengths that intersect and loop.

comments.comment: Yes - and maybe there's a way to let people know distances between common destinations - paint it on the sidewalk, plaques on buildings...

Yes! This could be a great way to engage broad swaths of the city to "show off" Cambridge to visitors, and for residents old and new to discover new things or enjoy their neighborhoods in a different and interesting way.

properties.description: Walking is a safe, accessible, and social form of exercise for people of all ages. The benefits of exercise are bountiful for body and mind. When people know how far they have walked and can establish a routine they are more likely to integrate it into their lives. Things like pieces of public art, historical homes, parks, and old trees can be highlighted. The online feature could be used to create walking buddies and walking groups. Walking with others enhances motivation and promotes community engagement.

properties.name: Amphitheater at the library park for plays, music and movies

comments.comment: This idea made it to the ballot (location was changed to Danehy Park), but didn't get enough votes to win funding.
Great idea!

properties.description: It would build a better community to have outdoor cultural activities that everyone could enjoy.

properties.name: Raised garden beds around the periphery of Raymond Park; upgrade of garden at Walden St. entrance

comments.comment: Two community garden projects (including improving the community garden in Raymond Park) made it to the ballot, but did not receive enough votes to win funding. A separate project for planting materials for residents and raised beds for food plants also made it to the ballot, but did not win funding.
Great idea!  Always seemed like someone should do more with that plot.  So many people pass by it everyday it would be a meaningful addition to the community.

properties.description: The circular garden at the Walden Street entrance to Raymond Park currently lies pretty fallow.  Perhaps it could become a community garden plot?  Raised garden beds along the park fencing might expand community gardening opportunities.  Perhaps garden plots could be adopted by neighborhood groups or after-school or nursery programs if individuals on community garden wait lists aren't available to garden.

properties.name: Artificial turf in Sennott Park in the playing area and additional benches

comments.comment: Not eligible - too expensive.

properties.description: The city is unable to maintain the grass and more people would like to sit on benches with backs

properties.name: protected bikelane on mass ave-Rt 16 to Porter sq.

comments.comment: Not eligible - too expensive.

properties.description: Install a two way, protected bikelane (with metal pillars for example) along mass ave.  get rid of one side of parking OR put the protected bike between parking and sidewalk.  Get rid of the median and retain only three traffic lanes.  Install overhead (or inroad if practical) lighting to allow two lanes of incoming traffic during am commute and 2 lanes of outgoing traffic during evening commute.

properties.name: Improvements at the Clarendon Ave tot lot/park

comments.comment: Budget Delegates researched this idea, but found that the City is already planning improvements at this location.

properties.description: The brick wall along mass ave is crumbling and needs to be fixed.  Also the water fountain needs to be fixed/improved (install the kind that can fill water bottles).  The "sand area" could also be cleaned and refresed with new sand.  The mass ave corner is a favorite hang-out for many of the senior citizens from the burns, so perhaps improve that area as well (must maintain the tree shade). Install a real (or Junior) basketball hoop in the circle so older kids could use the park in the evening.

properties.name: install more solar panels on the Daniel F. Burns apartments

comments.comment: Not eligible - not public property.

properties.description: I think the current system ther is 47Kw, but according to the cambridge solar mapping this huge roof could economically accomodate a 191 Kw system  This investment will make money for the city over time and helpf us reduce our carbon emissions

properties.name: Longer weekend hours at the library

comments.comment: Not eligible - would require operating funds. This idea was shared with the Library Director.
Let's extend the Sundays the library is open in the summer!
I guess this isn't a capital project, but there doesn't seem to be a way to erase my suggestion.

properties.description: Weekends are when most people want to use the library, but the hours tend to be shorter then. It cost something like $100 million, I heard, to reconstruct this library. The wonderful facility should get a lot more use than it does. But the biggest obstacle is that it just isn't open at the times that people want to use it.

properties.name: Add stop sign for traffic on Banks Street

comments.comment: Budget Delegates did not rank this as a high priority project. They shared the idea with the Traffic Department.

properties.description: This intersection is very dangerous for pedestrians and cyclists. The stop sign on Cowperthwaite street is on the left hand side and often missed by drivers, and on the right is a tall brick wall that obstructs drivers' view to Banks Street. If you are on a bike lawfully riding up Cowperthwaite, picking up speed to make it up the hill on Surrey, then you suddenly emerge from behind a wall to drivers zipping up Banks.

properties.name: Curb extension at Cambridge and Line Street

comments.comment: Budget Delegates did not rank this as a high priority project.

properties.description: The crosswalk is long, the right turn is fast and the pedestrian/vehicle sight line is terrible when there is a vehicle parked at the corner (metered parking here). There are a lot of pedestrians crossing here, including many elderly and caretakers with young children who are going to Cambridge Hospital. Please consider adding a curb extension at this location.

properties.name: Speed bumps on Line street

comments.comment: After visiting the site and taking notes on traffic, Budget Delegates did not rank this as a high priority project. The City does not support installation of speed bumps due to emergency vehicle response.
I love speeding along Line Street from Inman Sq. to Kirkland.. but this would make me slow down.. really good idea.

In 1978 I was a community organizer in Somerville--the eastern side of Line St. is in Somerville. At that time Somerville residents of the street asked for speed bumps but the cities said, "no." Now tht Cambridge has traffic calming I think this would be a good model for the street and could deliver something the residents asked for 36 years ago!
I'd like to add my support to the suggestion for traffic calming on Line Street. Given the straight downhill shot from around Cooney Street to Kirkland, speeding is a frequent problem.

Traffic calming on Line Street is a really great suggestion. There are no crosswalks except at Cambridge Street and Washington Street which is a long distance. As others have mentioned already, it is a fast cut through for vehicles trying to avoid Inman Square. Maybe raised crosswalks could be considered (on Line, Leonard and Magnolia). Line Street is part of the bicycle network plan too so improvements could be coordinated with those efforts.

This is a dangerous street in a section of the neighborhood with many children. Line street is used as a fast way to get from Cambridge st to Washington and Beacon streets with no lights, signs or intersections, though it links Cooney, Leonard ave, Magnolia and Smith streets, all dense with families.
A speed bump, a crosswalk and slow sign are all simple strategies that would have a huge effect and make the neighborhood safer for everyone.

A very much needed thing. In particular by the intersection Line street and Leonard Avenue (the riposted location) cars turn with a very high speed without looking for what is around the corner. With small children on this street getting cars to reduce the speed is vital.

properties.description: Line street is a very busy one way connecting Cambridge and Kirkland st. It is a high traffic road and vehicles often speed through or the occasional cars and motorcycles will race at high speed. Many pedestrians especially elderly and children use this road as it connects to Cambridge hospital and Beacon street as well. There have been several hit and run pedestrian incidents in the last few years and speed bumps would deter speeding and thus avoid future injury and accidents.

properties.name: Park Renovations and safety lights for Cambridgeport school playground

comments.comment: The Cambridgeport School playground has been funded for renovation through the Community Preservation Act.

properties.description: The school playground has unfortunately had issues with people spending the night, urinating and defecating on the playground at night causing rancid smells at the least and health safety concerns for children who play here by day. By installing motion sensor lighting especially in the rear which is often sight unseen we could deter unwanted nighttime activity. Along with a thorough cleaning and freshening up the playground (painting, new flooring etc) would be a much healthier environment for kids, teachers and parents.

properties.name: Book houses with multilingual first books for children. Near schools and tot lots.

comments.comment: This idea was split into two projects on the ballot. The first project, which won funding, was to purchase 300+ bilingual books for Cambridge children learning English through the Agenda for Children's Literacy Initiative.  The second, which did not receive enough votes to win funding, would have set up little free libraries/book houses around the city.
love the idea of lowering the height of the house so young kids could take one easily.

There are about five Free Little Libraries in Cambridge put up by residents. We put up one on Franklin Street and it has been great for engaging the neighborhood, who write great notes in the guestbook. The city supporting more of these seems like a good idea if paired with a clear responsibility for who will care for them. Perhaps it could be part of the responsibility for the librarian at the nearby school.

properties.description: Having your own books is important to beginning readers.  Providing free multilingual books in book houses on Cambridge streets near schools would provide first books for young readers who may be learning English and speaking other languages at home.  Suggest working with the Cambridge community engagement team which has a program to encourage parents reading to children at home.  For examples of book houses check existing "take a book/leave a book houses" on streets in Somerville and Boston - and build them lower so children can reach in and get a book.

properties.name: Shelters for school crossing guards.  Fletcher Maynard Academy, Windsor/Broadway and all schools.

comments.comment: Budget Delegates recommended this project for the ballot, but the City advised that the proposed location was not wide enough to accommodate shelters without obstructing driver and pedestrian views or hindering sidewalk accessibility.

properties.description: Crossing guards stand outside in the weather for an hour in the morning and two hours in the afternoon to safely cross Cambridge students to schools and buses.  During bad weather crossing guards would benefit by being able to warm up or not have to stand in pouring rain during wait times when they are not guiding students across the street.  The shelters could be portable and foldable so they could be stored in the school building; or perhaps in a business if the crossing guard works on the route but not right outside the school.  A Boy Scout in South Dakota built a model for crossing guards so it can be done!

properties.name: an improve playground for the Amigos School

comments.comment: Budget Delegates did not rank this as a high priority project.
Hi, My son spends every afternoon at the playground for about an hour, and I or my husband sit on the ground watching him play.  some benches, a fence, some upgrades would be fabulous.
At a minimum, can you change the asphalt surface between the two play structures and replace the wood chips? I also think the smaller green play structure is too small for the kids using the space.
It is unacceptable that the City of Cambridge can't provide a public school, with 300+ students, a decent playground but can afford endless city project renovations.
Yes, a new playground is needed at the Amigos School.  It would benefit the students, the teachers and the surrounding community.  Thank you for your consideration of this project.

The Amigos playground is substandard. A decent planner should take a look at the space, perhaps in a participatory charette and design something that works better. It is small and will never be the great playground the school had on Kinnaird/Putnam but it can be better than it is now.

Moving to the old Webster School was great in many ways but the playground situation was a known drawback.  Since Amigos will be in this space for the foreseeable future, improving the outdoor space will reap benefits for many years and many kids!
An improved playground for the school and the neighbourhood is sorely needed.

I completely agree that Amigos really needs a up-to-date playground. The wood chips in particular are terrible - it sometimes seems like more end up on the sidewalk and across the street than on the actual playground. It would take some creativity, but creating a playground that can work for all kids (at the school and in the neighborhood) should be doable!
Planting grass, a new play structure and making the basketball court safer
The children at Amigos deserve an improved playground that will allow them to be save and be creative. PLEASE make this happen!

I also advocate for a change in the Amigos playground. I worked with the city when moving into this location and they advised us to live with it for a year. We have lived with it for a few years. The garden is better than I thought it could be, but I often hear that kids get hurt or just sit around uninspired. The playground as it is, currently requires lots of adult interaction to supervise and engage children positively. This is not always available. When not available, kids are restricted to even smaller areas of the play area.
I would love to see a change to the soft cover and a way to keep that soft cover inside the playground. It is unsafe to walk across the playground if you are not paying attention to the steep dip under the climbing structure. Additionally, the sidewalks in front of the school are unsafe for walking most of the year because they are covered in Mulch. The fix tried this year did not work. I would also like to see imaginative play incorporated into the design. A container full of loose items and balls would be a great addition to this play area. My son suggests an obstacle course and my daughter would love to have some swings. One more thing, the current fence has some loose connections and is becoming unsafe (especially when children climb on the loose sections). Thank you for your consideration.

Please! this is a real need. The Amigos playground is in no way comparable to the playgrounds I have seen in the rest of the Cambridge schools. Space is limited but with some imagination and funds it could be a sweet fun and safe space.

last year my daughter got a concussion on the small, cramped Amigos playground when she was pushed into the jungle gym during a crowded recess. i agree that with the others who are posted that there aren much better ways to use the space they have. King school could use a better playground as well. Perhaps improving both playgrounds could be integrated into the city's program to employ teenagers during the summertime.

Woodchips as a soft ground cover have not worked for Amigos.  The chips retain water, get muddy and fall out upon the sidewalk.  At the very least install a play surface like those at the Kennedy-Longfellow or Peabody school playgrounds.  Parity, please!
I totally agree with all the comments here.  Amigos needs a playground that is on par with others across the city.  There is much that can be done with even this small space!

This is a real need. The playground is pretty sad. Partly the issue is upgrades, especially of ground cover. Partly, there should be some creative thinking of what could be done with the  limited space. If there was something that wouldn't normally work in a park during the winter, it might still work here -- and get folded up or dismantled each winter.

Absolutely. It should not be that hard to add at least a slide and monkey bars at a minimum. Better ground cover and swings also would not hurt. Amigos has the worst playground of all Cambridge schools, it would only be fair to improve it.
This is really needed. We should do this for our kids.

Sorry to comment twice, but I'd like to add that when Cambridge did comprehensive planning around school facilities, the Amigos location at Upton Street was not included - I think because it was not a school at the time - and no improvements were slated as part of the regular school capital planning.

The playground space at Amigos is terrible, unless you like an all-pavement space with no swings, no grass, and no trees. I would love to see an improved park-like yard, available also for the neighborhood.

properties.description: It would create enough safe playground space for students at recess and improve the community playground space for the neighborhood.

properties.name: Cookery School For Kids and Families

comments.comment: Not eligible - not public property.
Hmmm. I find a Cambridge Cookery School in the UK.  Closer to home, how about a community kitchen at the empty lot on Cherry Street?

properties.description:
Here at the Cambridge Cookery School families can strengthen their bonds over cooking lessons from the top local chefs. Kids will strengthen their knowledge of math and science through cooking--like hiding cauliflower in mashed potatoes! 

Family, food, and education, three things that are indispensable for a strong community.

properties.name: Installation of photovoltaic panels for electricity production on city owned buildings

comments.comment: The Water Department, City Hall Annex, King Open School, and Kennedy Longfellow School will have PV panels. Budget Delegates did not rank this as a high priority project.

Nice idea. According to the Cambridge interactive solar map, if the city invested $500k to put solar on the roof of my daughter's school (for example), it would generate the equivalent of 72,298 hours of air conditioning!

properties.description: It would drive down city electricity costs enhancing available discretionary funds, for years to come.  It will also help the environment by advancing the replacement of fossil fueled energy sources.

properties.name: Create a makerspace at the Cambridge Public Library

comments.comment: Budget Delegates did not move this idea forward, because the Library Director said that they are already thinking about creating a makerspace.

Yes, reinforcing the importance of the library, I love it! This is very similar to a suggestion under Culture and Community Facilities about creating a tool library; I see this as an extension of that.

properties.description:
We at the precipice of a technological revolution. In the words of Neil Gershenfeld, once upon a time computers were large bulky machines that took up an entire room and were operated by people with specialized training. This is quite similar to fabrication and manufacturing technology today: for the most part the things we use are created by large specialized machines by people with specialized knowledge. 

Tools for digital fabrication such as 3D printers and CNC machines mark a turning point in the evolution of how we make things. Democratizing access to these relatively expensive tools perhaps can inspire a generation and reinforce the cultural importance of the library (as has been done in other cities).

properties.name: Purchase more vehicles with tree-watering capacity.

comments.comment: Watering vehicles not eligible - would require operating funds. However, a project for 100 new trees won funding.

properties.description:
Too often the City's sidewalk trees don't thrive or just die because they don't get sufficient water when they need it.  Constantly replanting new trees is expensive and defeats the purpose of "growing" our green, urban canopy.

& while we're at it, plant/care for more trees.

properties.name: Whittemore Avenue Community Garden

comments.comment: Not possible to purchase the land in the suggested location. Two community garden projects made it to the ballot, but did not receive enough votes to win funding.
Great idea!

properties.description: Purchase the land and reestablish the community garden at this location.

properties.name: New park entrance on Walden Street

comments.comment: Not feasible - City-owned parcel leads to private property, so there is no through connection to the park.

properties.description: Make use of the city-owned parcel at this location to connect the park to Walden Street.

properties.name: Converting infrastructure of Foundry Building into Full Service Homeless Shelter,etc.

comments.comment: Not eligible - too expensive and would require operating funds. City Council is currently reviewing options for future uses of the building.
Yes, the homelessness issues need to be addressed immediately before park beautification, bike racks, play structures, etc.

properties.description: My project idea is to convert the infrastructure of the Foundry Building, at  101 Rogers Street in Cambridge Massachusetts, into shelter spaces and units, to address homelessness, and for the providing of supportive affordable housing services, etc. My project idea begins with the hiring of a Nonprofit Consultant, that specializes in Homelessness/Housing and Urban Development (HUD) issues and priorities, for Capacity Building, and to work diligently and collaboratively, with the Cambridge Continuum of Care (CoC),its Working Group on Homelessness, Alliance of Cambridge Tenants (ACT), and other community entities that serve our local poor populations, based on those with the greatest needs, such as the homeless, and other low income subgroups.

properties.name: address dangerous intersection at Fresh Pond Parkway and Huron Ave

comments.comment: Not eligible - not City property (belongs to state).

The big problem here as through much of the city's big intersections is right on red. If the signal were set up with signage that only allows right turns and left turns with arrows during most of the day, it would be vastly improved. No need for raised anything.
Sorry -- meant Windman. Fat fingers.

I live half a block away from this intersection, walk, bike, run and walk the dogs there. Totally agree with Eindman's idea. Because this intersection gets such heavy traffic, greater controls are needed and this would be a good beginning.

This intersection is incredibly dangerous.  We live 4 houses away and see cars run that light regularly. It is a heavily used 4-way pedestrian crossing and also a designated bike route.  I don't feel comfortable letting my children cross there but rather send them down to another cross walk to cross Huron.

Let's make it a raised intersection with pedestrian (and emergency vehicle) controlled signal lights! Let's widen the sidewalks and lower speeds. Let's get the out of town commuters using this road out of their cars and on a bike, a train, or a bus! Turn it into a toll road!

properties.description:
Pedestrians at risk due to speeding, inattentive drivers, poor signal timing, and lack of signage.
I would like to point out an easily addressed aspect of the dangerous intersection of Fresh Pond Parkway and Huron Avenue.
This crossing is the site of at least one pedestrian fatality that I know of. 
We need "a no right turn on red" here. 

At present Westbound( toward the Charles River) traffic is permitted to turn right on red, despite the fact that the pedestrian crossing sign says "go."
The slope and configuration of this intersection for some reason encourages drivers to treat it as a speed way, resulting in dangerous behavior when turning right from the Parkway onto Huron Ave. 
Drivers may or may not actually stop before turning right on red, but few look at the cross walk they are about to speed through. 
There are many close calls every hour. Close calls are precursors to catastrophe, but they do not appear in the city data.

properties.name: Redesign intersection of Rindge Ave and Sherman St.

comments.comment: Budget Delegates felt that this is a traffic timing issue and shared the idea with the Traffic Department.
Yes!  This simple change would make a huge difference!
This is a great idea! Traffic in Rindge got so much worse after they repainted the lines. Bravo!

properties.description: The yellow lines on Rindge at Sherman were redrawn recently. This small change had an oversized impact to traffic and, subsequently, quality of life in my North Cambridge neighborhood. The reason for this is that the previous width of the street allowed cars continuing straight on Rindge Ave to go around those waiting to take a left on Sherman Street. Now, if one car waits to take a left, every other car behind them misses the light as well. This routinely causes backups all the way to the Peabody School. This is a largely residential area, so it impacts residents and those trying to drop their children off at school and make their way to work. My idea has two options: The first is to redraw the double yellow lines to accommodate cars continuing straight on Rindge Ave - so they do not have to wait behind those taking a left on Sherman Street. The second is to add a delayed green light allowing cars to take a left before those traveling the opposite direction get the green light.

properties.name: Raised Crosswalk

comments.comment: Budget Delegates felt that this is a traffic timing issue and shared the idea with the Traffic Department.

properties.description: Drivers constantly disrespect the pedestrian crossing in front of the park entrance. A raised crosswalk would help reduce the driving speed and better mark the entrance to the park.

properties.name: Better Lighting

comments.comment: Budget Delegates did not rank this as a high priority project.

properties.description: This is a widely used path to cross the park and has no light posts.

properties.name: Less Oppressive Barrier

comments.comment: Budget Delegates researched this idea, but found that it was not feasible since the fence is protecting the water supply.
There are surely unfenced reservoirs in the world. I completely agree that it's horrible.
LOL. So people can hop it and or place kids/pets to swim in the reservoir?
Yes please!!!!

properties.description: The chain-link fence surrounding the pond is oppressive and detracts from the experience of enjoying this amenity. A much lower and better designed barrier would serve the same purpose, and enhance the park-like experience.

properties.description: There is a great opportunity to rethink how the MIT campus engages with the riverfront. Would be great to expand the public space along the river's edge by reducing the medians and improving pedestrian crossings. Would require working with the DCR abd MIT to make it happen.

properties.name: Cycle track (protected bike lane)

comments.comment: Not eligible - too expensive.
If the city considers biking to be important it should make a cycle track on Mass Ave - this is Cambridge's most centrally utilized street!
Great idea. Recent Cambridge Bicycle Network Plan confirms that more people would ride bicycles as commuters if there were raised cycle tracks.

properties.description: Mass. Ave. is dangerous for bikers.  We need a cycle track (protected bike lane) on Mass. Ave. northbound after Harvard, similar to the one on Western Ave.

properties.name: Extend the cycle track beyond Western Ave

comments.comment: Not eligible - too expensive.  City is working on a plan to get the reconstruction of River Street (which would include this area) into the five-year capital budget.  Design of streets, sidewalk, and bicycle accommodation would be part of the community process.

properties.description: Mass Ave is dangerous for bikers, so it would be great to extend the cycle track (protected bike lane) beyond Western Ave. to improve safety.

properties.name: Improve signage for Magazine Beach

comments.comment: Budget Delegates did not rank this as a high priority project.

properties.description: There is no signage for the park.  More signage is needed on Memorial Drive, Magazine Street, and the surrounding area.

properties.name: Improve area around Foundry Building

comments.comment: Budget Delegates did not rank this as a high priority project.

properties.description: This area is secluded and dark.

properties.name: Light sensors and surface repair for tennis courts at Hoyt Field and Riverside Park

comments.comment: Budget Delegates did not rank this as a high priority project.

properties.description: The lights are off at night, but having light sensors would allow people to use the courts after dark while also conserving energy when the courts are not in use.

properties.name: Community garden at Donnelly Field

comments.comment: Two community garden projects made it to the ballot, but did not receive enough votes to win funding.

Great idea! Making the space hospitable and attractive by introducing some biodiversity, in the form of community gardens and perhaps some other types of plants, would benefit all ages. If there is space, a tree-climbing (or log-climbing, or boulder-climbing) area would address some of the disparity in true green habitats that children enjoy in West/North Cambridge. While Donnelly Field can't be transformed into a Danehy Park or Fresh Pond Reservation, some aspects of those open spaces should be made available in Area 3 and 4 as much as possible. I don't mean to minimize the importance of organized sports, but opportunities for free, unstructured outdoor play in and amongst trees and fields is just as important for developing children and youth (and adults!). See also this proposal: http://shareabouts-pbcambridge.herokuapp.com/place/291227

Areas 3 and 4 contain the largest concentration of public housing in the city, and provide only very limited access to locally grown and produced food.  While Donnelly Field is a great and widely used sports complex in the center of the Wellington Harrington neighborhood, abutting the King Open School, the Frisoli Youth Center, a Head Start preschool and a branch library, the accessibility of the green space for the fields is primarily limited to sporting events, using three ball diamonds.  Careful reconfiguration of a part of this space could provide much greater local access to opportunities to grow one's own fresh vegetables and flowers, while maintaining the space's present use as ballparks.  This would provide enhanced opportunities for people in the neighborhood to gather, interact, and strengthen the health of, and connection between citizens of the neighborhood.

properties.description:
The younger generation is more obese than ever and many studies point to the lack of active transportation in their lives.  To inspire independence in our children and teach them to navigate our streets by biking and walking, the Dutch present a proven model called the Traffic Garden.  "The school curriculum includes regular field trips to the local 'traffic garden.' The City of Utrecht has used this facility, a streetscape in miniature, to teach kids the rules of the road since the 1950s. Students take turns as cyclists, pedestrians and car drivers, learning how to take other types of street users into consideration. The hands-on experience navigating the traffic garden gives kids the skills and confidence to get around the city under their own power as soon as their early teens" (http://vimeo.com/31545084).

We need a game changer for our health, environment, education and community and the traffic garden checks all the boxes.

If the city started this, I bet other people would donate their own extra tools. There would need to be some checking to make sure the tools are in safe condition, or maybe people could just sign that they take responsibility for potentially broken tools when they check it out.

properties.name: Crosswalk warning lights embedded in the road on Mass. Ave at the intersection of Garfield Street.

properties.description: This intersection is used by students, shoppers, and walkers, and runners to connect across Mass. Ave. in a district with shopping, restaurants, and bus stops. It's a large 4 lane crosswalk area between two sets of traffic lights. Drivers often ignore or don't see pedestrians in this crosswalk because they are looking ahead to the next set of traffic lights. A system with embedded lights would help signal simultaneously to the 4 lanes of traffic that someone is waiting to cross the road. Crossing the road is currently a game of leapfrog from one lane to the next. One lane of traffic might stop but the other lane, going in the same direction, might not stop. It also feels unsafe to cross 2 lanes and then wait at the small median in order to cross the second set of 2 lanes while traffic on both sides rushes past.

properties.name: A cross town separated bike lane so people could bike from Ailwife to East Cambridge

Ave. can't have protected bike lanes all at once from the Charles River to Arlington (which should be our goal), how about identifying a few blocks that have minimal curb cut conflict and could be reconstructed sooner rather than later? comments.comment: Budget Delegates did not rank this as a high priority project.

Great idea. In addition, this should be a model protected intersection for bikes. The fully protected curb separation for bike lanes on Vassar Street should continue into this intersection, and it should be designed for separate bike phasing (could overlap with pedestrian phasing) with islands and separate protected areas for bikes to queue and make turns. It's only a matter of time before another person is killed riding a bike (or walking) through this intersection. Every day is a series of close calls and intense vehicle-human conflict. The use demand here should prioritize walking and biking. This should be a safe, comfortable university and community plaza instead of a long-wait, frightening intersection.
